<p>
  Stardance is run by Hack Club, a 501(c)(3) nonprofit for teens. We collect
  the minimum information we need to run the program safely and ship prizes to
  the right places.
</p>

<h2>Birthday</h2>

<p>
  Stardance is built specifically for teens aged 13–18. Your birthday lets us
  confirm you're in that range and apply the right protections — for example,
  accounts under 13 aren't allowed under
  <abbr title="Children's Online Privacy Protection Act">COPPA</abbr>.
</p>

<p>
  We use your birthday for eligibility checks. It doesn't appear on your
  profile and we don't share it outside the program.
</p>

<h2>Region</h2>

<p>
  Region is about the shop. Different prizes are available in different
  parts of the world — some items can't legally be shipped everywhere, and
  some partners only support specific countries. Knowing your region up
  front means the things you see in the shop are things you can actually
  earn and receive.
</p>

<h2>Address (when you ship a project)</h2>

<p>
  When you ship your first project, we'll ask for your address. There are
  two reasons:
</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>For nonprofit recordkeeping.</strong> Hack Club is a 501(c)(3)
    nonprofit, which means the
    <abbr title="Internal Revenue Service">IRS</abbr> requires us to
    document that the value we give out is reaching specific, identifiable
    recipients — not looping back inside the organization. Keeping your
    address on file is part of that paper trail.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>So we can send you prizes.</strong> When you redeem Stardust
    for a physical item from the shop, we need somewhere to mail it.
  </li>
</ol>

<p>
  That's the whole list. We don't sell your address or use it for marketing.
  If you want to review or delete what we have on file, the request form is
  linked from the Hack Club privacy policy (linked at the bottom of this
  page).
</p>

<h2>What we don't do</h2>

<ul>
  <li>We don't sell your data.</li>
  <li>We don't run ads on Stardance.</li>
  <li>
    Your info never leaves Hack Club. The only people who can see it are
    the program team, all of whom are under a Hack Club NDA — no other
    teens, no partners, no external services.
  </li>
</ul>

<p>
  For the full picture, read the
  <%= link_to "Hack Club privacy policy", "https://hackclub.com/privacy", target: "_blank", rel: "noopener" %>.
</p>
